          <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-ink mb-4 dark:text-on-primary">How to Qualify as a Hong Kong Tax Resident: Rules and Calculator</h1>
          <p class="text-lg text-body dark:text-muted">Last updated: July 2026 | 10 min read</p>

          <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-body dark:text-muted">
            <p>Hong Kong tax residency determines who is subject to salaries tax, property tax, and profits tax. Under Hong Kong's territorial tax system, tax residents are taxed on income sourced in Hong Kong, while non-residents may have different exposure. This guide explains the legal definitions of tax residency, ordinary residency, the 60-day rule, permanent place of residence, and how residency affects your tax obligations. Use our <a href="/countries/hong-kong/salaries-tax/salaries-tax-calculator" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong tax calculator</a> to estimate your potential tax.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Definition of Tax Residency</h2>
            <p>A Hong Kong tax resident is generally any individual who resides in Hong Kong or has a close connection to the territory. For individuals, the IRD tests residency using two main concepts: ordinary residency and ordinary presence. Ordinary residency means residing in Hong Kong from choice, with a settled, voluntary, and permanent character. Ordinary presence looks at the number of days spent in Hong Kong during the year and in preceding years, plus other connections such as employment, business interests, family, and property.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Ordinary Resident vs. Ordinary Presence</h2>
            <p>Ordinary residency is broader than just physical presence. You may be considered an ordinary resident even if you spend time outside Hong Kong, provided your main home, family, and business remain in Hong Kong. Ordinary presence considers whether you have been present in Hong Kong for more than 180 days in the year of assessment, or for 300 days over two consecutive years. The IRD applies both tests flexibly, and no single factor is decisive. Factors such as maintaining a Hong Kong home, having family in Hong Kong, and holding a Hong Kong employment contract all support ordinary residency.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">The 60-Day Rule for Individuals</h2>
            <p>Section 8 of the Inland Revenue Ordinance provides that an individual who stays in Hong Kong for a total of 60 days or fewer in a year of assessment is exempt from salaries tax for that year. This rule applies to individuals who are not ordinarily resident in Hong Kong. The 60 days are counted on the basis of physical presence, and the IRD provides guidance on how to count arrival and departure days. It is important to note that the exemption does not apply to property income or business profits, which are assessed independently. Expats should be mindful of this rule when planning their travel schedules. See our <a href="/blogs/hong-kong-tax-calculator-expats-guide" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">expat tax guide</a> for more on planning strategies.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Permanent Place of Residence</h2>
            <p>Permanent place of residence is one of the indicators of ordinary residency, but it is not the sole test. Having a permanent place of residence in Hong Kong does not guarantee tax residency if you live abroad for most of the year. Conversely, you may be a tax resident even without owning property in Hong Kong if you can demonstrate other strong ties. The IRD looks at the overall picture, including the stability and permanence of your residence arrangements.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Tax Treaty Benefits</h2>
            <p>Hong Kong's double tax agreements include tie-breaker rules for individuals who may be considered residents of two jurisdictions. Under these rules, permanent residents of both jurisdictions are subject to mutual agreement, or failing agreement, they are residents of the jurisdiction where they have a permanent home available, closer personal and economic relations, and habitual abode. For dual residents, obtaining a certificate of residence from the IRD is often the first step to securing treaty benefits. Refer to <a href="https://www.ird.gov.hk" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">ird.gov.hk</a> for the latest list of agreements.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Residency for Property Tax</h2>
            <p>Property tax is levied on the owner of land or buildings in Hong Kong, regardless of residency. Therefore, even non-residents who own property in Hong Kong may be subject to property tax on the rental income. The net assessable value is calculated after deducting irrecoverable rental income and allowances. Learn more in our <a href="/blogs/hong-kong-property-tax-guide" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong property tax guide</a>.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Residency for Profits Tax</h2>
            <p>Profits tax applies to profits from a business, trade, or profession carried on in Hong Kong, regardless of the individual's residency. The key test for individuals is whether the trade, profession, or business is carried on in Hong Kong. For corporations, residency is determined by place of incorporation and central management and control. Use our <a href="/countries/hong-kong/profits-tax/profits-tax-calculator" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong profits tax calculator</a> to model your potential tax obligations.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">How do I prove I am a Hong Kong tax resident?</h3>
            <p>You can demonstrate ordinary residency by maintaining a permanent home, family, employment, and financial interests in Hong Kong. The IRD may also consider your pattern of visits over several years. For treaty purposes, apply for a certificate of residence from the IRD.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Can I be a tax resident of two countries?</h3>
            <p>Yes, under dual residency scenarios, Hong Kong's double tax tie-breaker rules determine which jurisdiction has taxing rights. Check the specific provisions in the relevant double tax agreement.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">What is the 60-day rule?</h3>
            <p>The 60-day rule exempts non-ordinarily resident individuals from salaries tax if they spend 60 days or fewer in Hong Kong during the year. It is an important planning tool for expats and cross-border workers.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Do I need to pay tax if I am not a resident?</h3>
            <p>Non-residents may still be taxed on Hong Kong-sourced income, such as rental income from Hong Kong property or profits from a Hong Kong business. Non-resident individuals may also be subject to salaries tax if they derive employment income from a Hong Kong employer and perform duties in Hong Kong.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Can I apply for a tax residency certificate?</h3>
            <p>Yes, the IRD issues certificates of residence for individuals and companies who wish to claim benefits under a double tax agreement. Submit an application with supporting evidence of your residency status.</p>
